  "texts": [
    "1253, 1278 (2009) (\"[R]eason-giving promotes accountability by limiting the scope of available discretion and ensuring that public officials provide public-regarding justifications for their decisions.\").",
    "91 See Lazar, supra note 87, at 14 (\"[C]onsent's moral effectiveness depends in part on its being public; the same is true for authori[z]ation.\").",
    "92 See id.",
    "at 42 (\"If explainability duties are grounded in the publicity requirement, which itself is grounded in the values of legitimacy and authority, then explainability duties are owed to the same people who are owed legitimacy and authority.",
    "These values are, in turn, grounded in individual freedom, relational equality, and collective self-determination.\")."
